\fs30 \cf4 \cb5 Recent computational advances allow investment managers to methodically\cb1 \
\cb5 search through thousands or even millions of potential options\cb1 \
\cb5 for a protable investment strategy. In many instances, the resulting\cb1 \
\cb5 strategy involves a pseudo-mathematical argument, which is\cb1 \
\cb5 spuriously validated through a simulation of its historical performance\cb1 \
\cb5 (also called backtest).\cb1 \
\cb5 We prove that high performance is easily achievable after backtesting\cb1 \
\cb5 a relatively small number of alternative strategy congurations, a\cb1 \
\cb5 practice we denote \\backtest overtting." The higher the number of\cb1 \
\cb5 congurations tried, the greater is the probability that the backtest is\cb1 \
\cb5 overt. Because nancial analysts rarely report the number of congurations\cb1 \
\cb5 tried for a given backtest, investors cannot evaluate the degree\cb1 \
\cb5 of overtting in most investment claims and analysis.\cb1 \
\cb5 The implication is that investors can be easily misled into allocating\cb1 \
\cb5 capital to strategies that appear to be mathematically sound\cb1 \
\cb5 and empirically supported by a backtest. This practice is particularly\cb1 \
\cb5 pernicious, because due to the nature of nancial time series,\cb1 \
\cb5 backtest overtting has a detrimental eect on the strategy's future\cb1 \
\cb5 performance.\cb1 \
