\fs30 \cf4 \cb5 This article addresses one of the most critical vulnerabilities in quantitative finance and algorithmic trading: backtest overfitting and data mining bias. Traditional performance metrics, such as Sharpe ratios, frequently suffer from selection bias, identifying parameters that maximize historical returns but fail catastrophically in out-of-sample conditions. To mitigate this structural dependency, this study introduces the KaC Ratio, a novel hybrid evaluation metric that multiplies an asset\'92s risk-adjusted return (Sharpe Ratio) by the linearity of its cumulative equity curve (R\'b2). To validate its empirical robustness and demonstrate its statistical invariance, a multidimensional macro-audit framework was designed. The KaC Ratio was subjected to stress tests against 20 classic and contemporary financial ratios across a cross-sectional universe of 600 systematic strategy combinations (derived from overnight and post-settlement anomalies in 60 global futures contracts).\cb1 \
\cb5 The experimental architecture incorporated three static validation frameworks (training/test splits of 75/25, 50/50, and 25/75) and two dynamic, iterative schemes (Walk Forward Analysis and Robust Walk Forward Analysis). Performance distributions were aggregated through a non-parametric combinatorial framework using Borda Count rankings and a custom Position-Volatility Efficiency metric (PER analysis). Empirical results demonstrate that, while traditional ratios experience severe performance degradation under information scarcity (25/75 framework), the KaC Ratio functions as an exceptional defensive shield, as it exhibits the most stable opponent ranking of all analyzed ratios, performing well under any robustness analysis employed.\cb1 \
